('grammar','multiple_choice','If we _____ enough fuel, we would not need to divert.\nA) have\nB) had\nC) has\nD) having','B','B2','medium','conditional_forms','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('grammar','multiple_choice','The first officer _____ the pre-flight checklist while the captain reviewed the weather.\nA) completed\nB) was completing\nC) has completed\nD) completes','B','B1','medium','tense_usage','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('grammar','multiple_choice','ATC instructed us _____ hold over the ROMEO waypoint.\nA) for\nB) to\nC) at\nD) on','B','A2','easy','phraseology_grammar','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('grammar','multiple_choice','The autopilot _____ disconnected automatically when the system detected a fault.\nA) is\nB) was\nC) has\nD) were','B','B1','medium','passive_voice','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('grammar','fill_blank','Complete: The weather at our destination is _____ (significant) worse than forecast.','significantly','B1','medium','structural_accuracy','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('grammar','multiple_choice','We need to declare an emergency _____ our hydraulic system has failed.\nA) because\nB) although\nC) despite\nD) unless','A','B1','medium','structural_accuracy','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('grammar','multiple_choice','The TCAS _____ a resolution advisory just before we reached FL350.\nA) issued\nB) has issued\nC) issues\nD) issuing','A','B2','medium','tense_usage','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('grammar','fill_blank','Complete: The captain made the decision _____ (quick) to go around.','quickly','A2','easy','structural_accuracy','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('grammar','multiple_choice','Neither the altimeter _____ the airspeed indicator was showing correct readings.\nA) or\nB) nor\nC) and\nD) but','B','B1','medium','structural_accuracy','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('grammar','multiple_choice','We _____ fly above FL410 due to aircraft performance limitations.\nA) cannot\nB) must not\nC) should\nD) may','A','B1','medium','phraseology_grammar','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('grammar','multiple_choice','The windshear warning _____ activated during our final approach to Runway 23.\nA) is\nB) was\nC) has\nD) were','B','A2','easy','passive_voice','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('grammar','multiple_choice','By the time we reached the alternate, we _____ been flying for 6 hours.\nA) had\nB) have\nC) will\nD) would','A','B2','hard','tense_usage','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('grammar','fill_blank','Complete: The approach was _____ (extreme) challenging due to crosswinds.','extremely','B1','medium','structural_accuracy','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('grammar','multiple_choice','Each crew member _____ responsible for checking their own emergency equipment.\nA) is\nB) are\nC) were\nD) been','A','A2','easy','structural_accuracy','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('grammar','multiple_choice','The crew reported that they _____ experiencing severe icing at FL280.\nA) are\nB) were\nC) is\nD) has been','B','B1','medium','tense_usage','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('grammar','multiple_choice','We should _____ checked the NOTAMs before planning the route.\nA) had\nB) have\nC) has\nD) having','B','B2','medium','structural_accuracy','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('grammar','multiple_choice','The aircraft _____ cleared for the ILS approach to Runway 05.\nA) is\nB) was\nC) were\nD) been','B','A2','easy','passive_voice','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('grammar','multiple_choice','_____ we receive clearance, we cannot begin our descent.\nA) Until\nB) While\nC) During\nD) Since','A','B1','medium','structural_accuracy','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),

-- Reading (10)
('reading','multiple_choice','Read the ATC clearance:\n\n"Turkish 1923, cleared to Istanbul via ROMEO ONE ALPHA departure, climb and maintain FL180. Squawk 4512. Contact departure on 119.7 after airborne."\n\nWhat altitude should the aircraft climb to initially?\nA) FL120\nB) FL180\nC) FL240\nD) FL350','B','B1','medium','atc_clearance_reading','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('reading','multiple_choice','Read the METAR:\n\n"METAR LTFM 181200Z 24018G32KT 6000 TSRA SCT025CB BKN040 22/18 Q1008 TEMPO 2000 +TSRA"\n\nWhat weather phenomenon is occurring?\nA) Snow\nB) Thunderstorm with rain\nC) Fog\nD) Clear skies','B','B2','hard','weather_report_reading','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('reading','multiple_choice','Read the performance chart note:\n\n"WARNING: For runways with a slope greater than 2%, add 10% to the calculated takeoff distance. For wet runways, add 15%. These factors are cumulative — apply both corrections when both conditions exist."\n\nA runway has 2.5% slope and is wet. What total correction should be applied?\nA) 10%\nB) 15%\nC) 25%\nD) 20%','C','B2','hard','technical_manual','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('reading','multiple_choice','Read the NOTAM:\n\n"NOTAM C0156/26 — Crane operating near RWY 18 threshold, max height 85ft AGL, position 0.3nm south of threshold. Crane lit day and night. No effect on instrument approach minimums."\n\nWhere is the crane located?\nA) On the runway\nB) 0.3nm south of Runway 18 threshold\nC) At the airport terminal\nD) Near the control tower','B','B1','medium','notam_interpretation','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('reading','multiple_choice','Read the SID (Standard Instrument Departure) note:\n\n"ROMEO 1A DEPARTURE: After takeoff, climb runway heading to 2000ft, then turn right heading 090 to intercept the ROM R-120. Cross ABCDE at or above FL080. Maximum speed 250kt below FL100."\n\nWhat is the maximum speed below FL100?\nA) 200kt\nB) 250kt\nC) 300kt\nD) No limit','B','B1','medium','sop_comprehension','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('reading','multiple_choice','Read the fuel slip:\n\n"Aircraft: TC-FLY | Block Fuel: 18,400 kg | Trip Fuel: 12,200 kg | Contingency: 610 kg | Alternate: 2,800 kg | Final Reserve: 1,200 kg | Taxi: 400 kg | Extra: 1,190 kg"\n\nWhat is the minimum fuel required to reach the alternate airport?\nA) 12,200 kg\nB) 2,800 kg\nC) 18,400 kg\nD) 1,200 kg','B','B2','medium','technical_manual','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('reading','multiple_choice','Read the MEL (Minimum Equipment List) entry:\n\n"Item 34-12: Weather Radar — May be inoperative provided: (a) flight is conducted in VMC or where thunderstorms are not forecast, (b) operations are limited to day only, (c) captain accepts responsibility for weather avoidance."\n\nCan the aircraft fly at night without weather radar?\nA) Yes, with captain approval\nB) No, only day operations\nC) Yes, in any conditions\nD) Only if an alternate radar is available','B','B2','hard','technical_manual','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('reading','multiple_choice','Read the briefing card:\n\n"ATIS Information Charlie: Runway in use 36L. Wind 350/12kt. Visibility 8000m. Cloud FEW030, BKN060. Temperature 16, dew point 10. QNH 1018. Transition level FL70. Expect ILS approach."\n\nWhat is the QNH setting?\nA) 1008\nB) 1018\nC) 1028\nD) 1038','B','A2','easy','weather_report_reading','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('reading','multiple_choice','Read the emergency checklist extract:\n\n"ENGINE FIRE IN FLIGHT:\n1. Affected engine thrust lever — IDLE\n2. Affected engine fire handle — PULL\n3. If fire warning continues after 10 seconds — rotate handle to agent 1\n4. If fire warning continues — rotate handle to agent 2\n5. If fire warning continues — LAND AT NEAREST SUITABLE AIRPORT"\n\nWhat should be done first in an engine fire?\nA) Pull the fire handle\nB) Set the engine thrust to idle\nC) Rotate to agent 1\nD) Land immediately','B','B1','medium','sop_comprehension','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('reading','multiple_choice','Read the weight and balance note:\n\n"The aircraft centre of gravity must remain within the forward limit of 18% MAC and aft limit of 33% MAC throughout all phases of flight. Exceeding the aft limit may result in loss of pitch control."\n\nWhat happens if CG exceeds the aft limit?\nA) The aircraft uses less fuel\nB) Possible loss of pitch control\nC) The flight is more comfortable\nD) Nothing significant','B','B2','hard','technical_manual','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),

-- Writing (8)
('writing','written_response','You are a pilot. During cruise at FL370, you encountered unexpected severe turbulence that injured one cabin crew member. Write a brief incident report (at least 60 words) describing the event, actions taken, and the current status.','Model answer should include altitude, time, type of turbulence, injuries, ATC notification, diversion consideration, and crew status.','B2','hard','incident_report','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('writing','written_response','Write a message to your airline''s operations department requesting a route change for tomorrow''s flight due to volcanic ash reported along the planned route. Include the flight number, original route, and your proposed alternative (at least 50 words).','Model answer should include formal request, flight details, safety concern, alternative route suggestion.','B1','medium','operational_message','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('writing','written_response','You are the captain. Write a short entry in the aircraft technical log describing a cockpit warning light that illuminated during flight but later extinguished. Include what happened, the system affected, and your recommendation (at least 50 words).','Model answer should include specific system, time of occurrence, actions taken, MEL reference if applicable.','B1','medium','maintenance_log','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('writing','written_response','A new first officer will be joining your crew next week. Write a welcome email (at least 50 words) introducing yourself, describing what to expect on the first flight together, and offering to answer any questions.','Model answer should be professional yet welcoming, mention briefing procedures, CRM expectations.','A2','easy','operational_message','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('writing','written_response','Write a PIREP (Pilot Report) in narrative form (at least 50 words) reporting moderate icing you encountered between FL180 and FL220 during descent into Ankara. Include the type of icing, location, and advice for other pilots.','Model answer should include icing type, altitude range, location, OAT, recommendation.','B2','hard','technical_description','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('writing','written_response','You need to report a bird strike that occurred during takeoff. Write a brief report (at least 50 words) for the airline safety department including when, where, which part of the aircraft was struck, and any damage observed.','Model answer should include time, runway, phase of flight, impact location, damage assessment, action taken.','B1','medium','incident_report','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('writing','written_response','You are a captain writing feedback about a training flight with a cadet pilot. Describe their strengths and one area for improvement (at least 60 words).','Model answer should be constructive, specific, mention CRM skills, technical ability, and recommendation.','B2','medium','safety_report','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('writing','written_response','Write a brief fuel complaint report. Your aircraft consistently burns 8% more fuel than planned on the Istanbul-London route. Describe the issue, provide evidence, and suggest possible causes (at least 60 words).','Model answer should include specific route data, comparison with planned figures, possible causes like weather/weight/routing.','B2','hard','technical_description','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),

-- Speaking (8)
('speaking','audio_response','You are the captain making a passenger announcement. Inform passengers that you are beginning your descent into Istanbul, the weather there is sunny with 22°C, and you will be landing in approximately 25 minutes.\n\nSpeak for at least 30 seconds.','Expected: Professional PA tone, clear weather info, landing time, thank passengers.','A2','easy','cabin_announcement','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('speaking','audio_response','Roleplay: You are speaking to ATC. Report that you have a hydraulic system caution light and request priority handling for landing. State your position, altitude, and intentions.\n\nSpeak for at least 30 seconds.','Expected: Proper radio phraseology, callsign, position, nature of problem, request for priority.','B2','hard','roleplay_atc','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('speaking','audio_response','Describe what CRM (Crew Resource Management) means to you as a pilot. Why is it important? Give one example from your experience or training.\n\nSpeak for at least 45 seconds.','Expected: Definition of CRM, importance of communication/teamwork, concrete example, professional reflection.','B2','medium','oral_briefing','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('speaking','audio_response','You are briefing your first officer before a flight to London. Cover the weather, route, fuel status, and any special considerations for today''s flight.\n\nSpeak for at least 45 seconds.','Expected: Structured briefing, weather summary, route overview, fuel figures, NOTAMs awareness, CRM elements.','B1','medium','crew_coordination','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('speaking','audio_response','Explain what you would do if you lost all engine power at FL350. Describe your immediate actions and decision-making process.\n\nSpeak for at least 40 seconds.','Expected: Declare mayday, establish best glide, attempt restart, identify nearest airport, communicate with ATC/cabin crew.','B2','hard','roleplay_emergency','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('speaking','audio_response','Roleplay: You are the pilot speaking to a ground engineer on the intercom before departure. There is a discrepancy in the technical log that you want clarified before accepting the aircraft.\n\nSpeak for at least 30 seconds.','Expected: Professional tone, specific reference to log entry, clear question, safety-first attitude.','B1','medium','ground_communication','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('speaking','audio_response','Describe the standard approach briefing you would give before an ILS approach to Runway 05 at Antalya. Include the key elements.\n\nSpeak for at least 40 seconds.','Expected: Approach type, runway, frequencies, altitude constraints, go-around procedure, weather minima, threat assessment.','B2','medium','oral_briefing','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('speaking','audio_response','You are a training captain. A trainee asks you: "What was the most challenging situation you faced as a pilot?" Share a brief story and what you learned from it.\n\nSpeak for at least 45 seconds.','Expected: Narrative structure, specific situation, actions taken, lesson learned, relevance to safety.','B1','medium','oral_briefing','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),

-- Listening (12)
('listening','multiple_choice','[AUDIO] "Turkish 1923, descend and maintain flight level 180. Report reaching. Traffic 2 o''clock, 10 miles, opposite direction, a Boeing 777 at flight level 190."\n\nWhat altitude should the pilot descend to?\nA) FL190\nB) FL180\nC) FL170\nD) FL200','B','B1','medium','atc_phraseology','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('listening','multiple_choice','[AUDIO] "Pegasus 245, wind check: 270 degrees at 18 knots, gusting 28. Cleared to land Runway 27 Left. Caution: braking action reported medium to poor by preceding aircraft."\n\nWhat is the maximum wind gust?\nA) 18 knots\nB) 28 knots\nC) 27 knots\nD) 45 knots','B','B1','medium','atc_phraseology','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('listening','multiple_choice','[AUDIO] "All stations, all stations. Istanbul Approach. SIGMET information: severe turbulence reported by multiple aircraft between FL250 and FL350 in the area south of Istanbul. Pilots are advised to avoid this area if possible."\n\nWhat is being reported?\nA) Volcanic ash\nB) Severe turbulence between FL250-FL350\nC) Low visibility\nD) Engine failure','B','B2','medium','emergency_broadcast','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('listening','multiple_choice','[AUDIO] "SunExpress 402, hold short of Runway 36 Left. Traffic on final, 3 miles. Expect clearance in approximately 2 minutes. Monitor tower 118.1."\n\nWhat must the pilot do?\nA) Take off immediately\nB) Hold short of Runway 36L and wait\nC) Switch to departure frequency\nD) Cross the runway','B','A2','easy','atc_phraseology','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('listening','multiple_choice','[AUDIO] "Mayday, Mayday, Mayday. This is AnadoluJet 891. We have an engine fire, left engine. Currently at FL280, 45 miles southeast of Ankara. Requesting immediate vectors for Ankara Runway 03. Souls on board: 162."\n\nHow many people are on the aircraft?\nA) 89\nB) 162\nC) 280\nD) 45','B','B1','medium','emergency_broadcast','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('listening','multiple_choice','[AUDIO] "Turkish 1901, contact Istanbul Control on 132.4. Good day."\n\nWhat frequency should the pilot switch to?\nA) 118.1\nB) 121.5\nC) 132.4\nD) 119.7','C','A2','easy','atc_phraseology','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('listening','multiple_choice','[AUDIO] "Cabin crew report: The number 2 lavatory smoke detector activated during cruise. We investigated — a passenger was smoking. The cigarette has been extinguished and the passenger has been warned. No damage to the aircraft."\n\nWhat caused the smoke detector to activate?\nA) An electrical fire\nB) A passenger was smoking\nC) Engine smoke entered the cabin\nD) The detector malfunctioned','B','B1','medium','cockpit_communication','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('listening','multiple_choice','[AUDIO] "Flight crew, this is dispatch. Weather update for your destination: Istanbul Airport is now reporting 300 metres visibility in fog. The airport is currently CAT III operations only. Your aircraft is CAT IIIA certified. Confirm you are qualified for CAT III approach."\n\nWhat is the current visibility at Istanbul?\nA) 3000 metres\nB) 300 metres\nC) 30 metres\nD) 3 kilometres','B','B2','hard','cockpit_communication','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('listening','multiple_choice','[AUDIO] "Turkish 1923, turn left heading 270 for traffic avoidance. Expect radar vectors back to the ILS Runway 05 approach. Maintain 4000 feet."\n\nWhy must the pilot turn left?\nA) To line up with the runway\nB) To avoid other traffic\nC) Due to wind conditions\nD) For fuel saving','B','B1','medium','atc_phraseology','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('listening','multiple_choice','[AUDIO] "Ground, Pegasus 173 at Gate 5, requesting startup and pushback. We have ATIS information Delta. Two-five-zero-zero kilograms of fuel remaining to be loaded."\n\nWhat is the pilot requesting?\nA) Landing clearance\nB) Startup and pushback\nC) Taxi to runway\nD) Parking assignment','B','A2','easy','atc_phraseology','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
('listening','multiple_choice','[AUDIO] "Attention crew. We will be entering an area of known moderate to severe turbulence in approximately 15 minutes. Cabin service should be completed and secured. Cabin crew take your seats 5 minutes before entry. I will make a PA to passengers shortly."\n\nHow much warning time is given before turbulence?\nA) 5 minutes\nB) 10 minutes\nC) 15 minutes\nD) 20 minutes','C','A2','easy','cockpit_communication','general','flight_deck',true,true,1),
